# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arena-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:arena-football/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:arena-football/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:arena-football/1896-chicago-maroons-football-team] The **1896 Chicago Maroons football team** was an American football team that represented the University of Chicago during the 1896 Western Conference football season.
[src:arena-football/1896-chicago-maroons-football-team] In their fifth season under head coach Amos Alonzo Stagg, the Maroons compiled a 15–2–1 record, finished in fourth place in the Western Conference with a 3–2 record against conference opponents, and outscored their opponents by a combined total of 368 to 82.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The **1896 Michigan Wolverines football team** was an American football team that represented the University of Michigan in the 1896 Western Conference football season.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] In its first and only season under head coach William Ward, the team compiled a 9–1 record (2–1 against conference opponents), tied for second place in the Western Conference, and outscored opponents by a total of 262 to 11.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The team started the season with nine consecutive wins in which the Wolverines shut out eight opponents and outscored their opponents by a total of 256 to 4.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] In the final game of the season, played on Thanksgiving Day at the Chicago Coliseum, the team lost a close game to Amos Alonzo Stagg's Chicago Maroons by a score of 7–6.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The 1896 Chicago–Michigan rivalry game was the first college football game played indoors, and the last portion of the game was also played under electric lights.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Halfback Gustave Ferbert was the team's leading scorer with 56 points on six touchdowns (four points each) and 16 kicks for goal from touchdown (two points each).
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Tackle Frederick "Pa" Henninger led the team in touchdowns with nine.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Tackle Frank Villa and halfback Hazen Pingree Jr.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Pingree was elected Governor of Michigan during the football season) scored seven touchdowns each.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Before the 1896 football season took the field, two developments occurred.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] First, Michigan joined the Western Inter-collegiate Athletic Conference (later renamed the Big Ten Conference).
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The 1896 season was the first for Michigan in conference play.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan's three conference games in 1896 were against Purdue, Minnesota and Chicago.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Second, William McCauley, who had led Michigan to a 17–2–1 record in two seasons as coach, resigned as Michigan's football coach.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Princeton graduate, William Ward, was hired to replace McCauley.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Before leaving Ann Arbor in November 1896, McCauley assisted Ward in coaching the 1896 team.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan conducted tryouts for the 1896 football team at Sand Beach.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On October 3, 1896, Michigan defeated Michigan State Normal (later renamed Eastern Michigan University) by an 18–0 score at Regents Field in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Fletcher scored Michigan's first touchdown after 10 minutes.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Hazen Pingree Jr. scored the second touchdown on an end run.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] William Caley kicked both goals from touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] In the second half, Michigan scored on a safety.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Several minutes later, Henninger scored a touchdown on a three-yard run, but missed the kick for goal.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On October 10, 1896, Michigan defeated a Grand Rapids team by a 44–0 at Regents Field in Ann Arbor.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The Grand Rapids team was made up of high school men with the exception of McPhearson, who was the coach and played left end.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played in halves of 20 and 10 minutes.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Henninger scored a touchdown after two minutes of play, but the kick for goal was missed.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Three minutes later, Frank Villa scored Michigan's second touchdown, and the goal was again missed.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] At the 11-and-a-half minute mark, Villa scored Michigan's third touchdown, and William Caley kicked the goal.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Hazen Pingree Jr. scored the fourth touchdown on a run around left end for more than 60 yards.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Caley again kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 20–0, at halftime.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] In the second half, Michigan scored four touchdowns in 10 minutes.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan's second half touchdowns were scored by Henninger, Pingree, Palmer, and Thad Farnham.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Charles Steele kicked all four goals from touchdown in the second half.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On Thursday, October 15, 1896, Michigan defeated the Chicago Physicians and Surgeons by a 28–0 score at Regents Field in Ann Arbor.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played in 15-minute halves.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Villa scored Michigan's first touchdown on a 10-yard run, and Steele kicked the goal.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Ferbert scored the second touchdown on a 20-yard run, Steele again kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 12–0, at halftime.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Pingree scored Michigan's third touchdown six minutes into the second half.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Pingree scored the fourth touchdown, and Hogg's kick for goal failed.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Villa scored Michigan's fifth and final touchdown, and Hogg kicked the goal.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On October 17, 1896, Michigan defeated the team from Lake Forest College by a 66–0 at Regents Field in Ann Arbor.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan scored 13 touchdowns in the game: three by Gustave Ferbert, three by Edwin H.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Henninger, two by Frank Villa, and one each by Charles Juttner and Norwood Ayres.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Ferbert kicked seven goals from touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played in halves of 25 and 15 minutes.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan scored 40 points in the 15-minute second half.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On October 24, 1896, Michigan defeated Purdue by a 16–0 score before a crowd of 2,000 at Stuart Field in West Lafayette, Indiana.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Villa scored Michigan's first touchdown, and Ferbert kicked the goal to give Michigan a 6–0 lead at halftime.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] In the second half, Hogg scored a touchdown, but the kick for goal missed, and Michigan led, 10–0.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Late in the game, Caley scored a third touchdown for Michigan, and Ferbert kicked the goal to extend Michigan's lead to 16–0.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] When the Michigan football team arrived at the Ann Arbor railway station on Sunday afternoon following the Purdue game, the players were cheered by a large crowd.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The team was also greeted with red fire by Sid Millard.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On October 31, 1896, Michigan defeated Lehigh by a 40–0 score.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game, played in 30-minute halves, was watched by a crowd of between 2,000 and 3,000 spectators at the Detroit Athletic Club's field in Detroit.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan scored seven touchdowns: four by James Hogg, two by Gustave Ferbert, and one by Frederick W.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Ferbert also kicked five goals from touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] During the 60 minutes of play, the ball was in Lehigh's possession "not more than ten minutes," and most of that was in the first half.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] One newspaper account stated that "the Eastern boys were outclassed from start to finish." The same report noted: "The team play of the University of Michigan was excellent and the interference as good as has ever been seen in this city.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] No other team defeated Lehigh so soundly.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] National champion Princeton scored only 16 points against Lehigh; Penn was held to 34 points; and Navy scored only 24.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Because Lehigh played the top teams in the east, Michigan's large margin of victory was seen as important in measuring Michigan's standing.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The 1897 *Michiganensian* noted: "This was the only contest with an eastern team and furnished some basis for comparison. . . .
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On November 7, 1896, Michigan won by a 6–4 score over previously undefeated Minnesota.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played in 35-minute halves before 5,000 spectators at old Athletic Park in Minneapolis.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Right end Loomis Hutchinson of Michigan scored in the first half, but he was ruled offside and the touchdown was disallowed.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] After a scoreless first half, Michigan fullback Ignatius M.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Duffy was pushed over for a touchdown in the second half, and Gustave Ferbert kicked the goal from touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan fans in the bleachers celebrated Duffy's touchdown with cowbells.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Shortly thereafter, Minnesota scored a touchdown, but the score came at the far corner of the field where a straight kick for the goal after touchdown was impossible.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Accordingly, Minnesota attempted a double kick, kicking the ball first to the fullback Loomis.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On November 14, 1896, Michigan defeated Oberlin by a 10–0 score at Regents Field in Ann Arbor.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Oberlin was offside on the kickoff, giving Michigan the ball at midfield.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Duffy scored Michigan's first touchdown, and right halfback William Caley kicked the goal to give Michigan a 6–0 lead.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Later in the first half, right tackle Frederick W.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Henninger was pushed over the goal line for Michigan's second touchdown, and Caley missed the kick for goal.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] *The World* of New York reported that the game was seen by 1,000 persons and added: "Michigan put a substitute team against Oberlin to-day and won by making two touchdowns in the first half.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On November 21, 1896, Michigan played the team from Wittenberg College, prevailing by a 28–0 score.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played on a mud-covered Regents Field in Ann Arbor.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan scored six touchdowns: three by right halfback William Caley, two by left halfback Hazen Pingree Jr., and one by right end George Greenleaf.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Caley and left tackle Frank Villa each kicked one goal from touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The game was played in halves of 20 and 15 minutes.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Through the first nine games, Michigan was undefeated and had scored 256 points, shut out eight opponents, and given up a total of four points.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] On Thanksgiving Day, November 26, 1896, Michigan lost, 7–6, to Chicago before a crowd of between 15,000 and 20,000 persons at the Chicago Coliseum in Chicago.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] If Michigan had won, it would have been the Western Conference champion.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Chicago's scoring came on a blocked punt resulting in a safety and a drop kicked field goal (worth five points under the rules at the time) by Clarence Herschberger from the 45–yard line.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Michigan's sole touchdown came in the second half when Henninger was pushed across the goal line from the two-yard line, and Ferbert kicked the goal Michigan later drove the ball to Chicago's 15–yard line, but Michigan fumbled and Chicago recovered the ball.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] According to a newspaper account, the field grew dark in the second half, and play was halted for ten minutes to discuss whether play should continue.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Play was resumed, and the lights were finally turned on after Michigan scored a touchdown.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The crowd was stated in varying press accounts to be either 15,000, or 20,000.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Noting that the game was played in the same building "in which five months ago W.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] William Ward did not return as Michigan's football coach in 1897.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] Ward was a Princeton alumnus who studied medicine at Michigan.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] He wrote: "There are many interesting things in coaching, but there are also some drawbacks and disagreeable features, so that I was glad to be through with it, and able to give myself wholly to the study of medicine." Ward became a surgeon and was a pioneer in the development of artificial vaginas.
[src:arena-football/1896-michigan-wolverines-football-team] The following players were members of Michigan's 1896 varsity football team.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] The **1930 NFL season** was the 11th regular season of the National Football League.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Prior to the season, Brooklyn bootlegger Bill Dwyer bought the Dayton Triangles, moved them, brought on former Orange Tornadoes star Jack Depler as a partner, and renamed them the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] With this move, the league was able to keep the final franchise from the Ohio League alive, albeit in a new location and with more skilled players, as it was unfeasible for the players in Dayton to move to Brooklyn during the Great Depression.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] The remains of the Tornadoes, with much of their roster now playing for the relocated Triangles-Dodgers franchise, moved to Newark.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] The Portsmouth Spartans (now known as the Detroit Lions) joined the league, while the Buffalo Bisons and the Boston Bulldogs both folded.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] The Green Bay Packers were named the NFL champions for the second consecutive year after they finished the season with the best record.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Defending champion Green Bay won its first eight games, including a 14–7 home win over the New York Giants on October 4.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] By **Week Nine**, Green Bay was at 8–0–0 and New York right behind them at 10–1–0.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] On November 16, the Packers lost to the Cardinals 13–6, but in New York, the Giants fell to the Bears, 12–0.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] On November 23, a crowd of 37,000 turned out as the Packers and the Giants met at the Polo Grounds in New York.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Missed extra points had a big effect, as four days later, the Giants were beaten on Thanksgiving Day by Staten Island, 7–6, while Green Bay defeated Frankford 25–7 to retake the lead at 9–2–0 (.818) to New York's 11–3–0 (.785).
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] The Giants faltered again on Sunday, November 30, when Brooklyn beat them 7–6, again on a missed point after.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] In **Week Thirteen**, the Giants beat the Yellow Jackets, 14–6, while the Packers lost to the Bears, 21–0, cutting Green Bay's hold on first place to a mere 4/10ths of a percentage point, .769 to .765.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Once again, the point after decided the race.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] On December 14, the Packers scored on Red Dunn's touchdown pass to Wuert Engelmann, but the point after by Verne Lewellen failed, giving them a 6–0 lead.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] After Chuck Bennett ran for a touchdown for the Spartans, the extra point attempt by Tiny Lewis was blocked, and when the game ended, the 6–6 tie gave the Packers the 1930 title.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Had the current (post-1972) system of counting ties as half a win and half a loss been in place in 1930, the tie would have given the Giants (13–4–0, .765) the title, and Green Bay would have finished runner-up at .750.
[src:arena-football/1930-nfl-season] Tie games were not officially counted in the standings until 1972.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The **1932 NFL Playoff Game** was an extra game held to break a tie in the 1932 season's final standings in the National Football League (NFL); it matched the host Chicago Bears and the Portsmouth Spartans.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Because of snowfall and anticipated extremely cold temperatures in Chicago, Illinois, it was moved indoors and played at the three-year-old Chicago Stadium on December 18 on a reduced-size field on Sunday night.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The Bears won, beating the Spartans 9-0.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Since the NFL's first season in 1920, the league title had been awarded to the team with the best regular season record based on winning percentage with ties excluded.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] In 1932, the Spartans and the Bears tied for first place with 6–1 records.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Had pure win–loss differential or the current (post-1972) system of counting ties as half a win, half a loss been in place in 1932, the Packers' record of 10–3–1 (.750, +7) would have won them a fourth consecutive championship, ahead of the Spartans' 6–1–4 (.727, +5) and the Bears' 6–1–6 (.692, +5).
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The Packers controlled their own destiny at the end of the 1932 season, but lost their last two games to the Spartans and the Bears.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] As the two Bears-Spartans games ended in 13–13 and 7–7 ties, this tiebreaker was of no effect.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The league was thus required to make a rule change, as championship-deciding postseason matches were banned in 1924, and for the first time, arranged for a single game (essentially a replay) to determine the NFL champion.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Despite the winner of the game being declared champions, it was ruled the game would be counted in the final standings, meaning the loser would drop to 6–2 (.750) and finish third behind runner-up Green Bay.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The game was set to be played at Wrigley Field, the Bears' home stadium, but due to severe blizzards followed by extremely cold temperatures and wind chill, the game was moved indoors to Chicago Stadium.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The Stadium at that time was the largest indoor arena in the world with a maximum seating capacity of 26,000.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Two years earlier, the Bears and Cardinals had played a charity exhibition game at the arena after the 1930 season.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The game was moved indoors due to extreme weather, allowing for reasonable attendance and gate revenue.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] It wasn't an uncommon practice in the city, as local teams played in the Dexter Park Pavilion as early as 1917, when the Racine Cardinals and the Evanstons from Evanston played to a scoreless tie.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] A week before the game, the concrete surface had tanbark placed atop for a Salvation Army-sponsored circus; elephant manure from the circus produced an odor that caused a Bears player to vomit on the field.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] It was also decided that due to the smaller field and indoor stadium, drop kicks and field goals would not be used in the game.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The high temperature for that Sunday in Chicago was 20 °F (−7 °C), warmer than anticipated earlier in the week.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] With terrible footing on the mulch and limited room for the offenses to work, the defenses dominated the game's first three quarters, with the game remaining scoreless.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Bears quarterback John Doehling's first pass flew into the stands, as did most punts and kickoffs: one collided with a Chicago Black Hawks sign and another hit the organist as he played.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] By the end of the game, only one punt had been returned.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] On one drive, the Spartans were in position to score when Glenn Presnell tripped on the field before he could reach the end zone.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] For the Bears, they employed a heavy run game with fullback Bronko Nagurski, though possessions ended after just three downs as Ralph Jones frequently elected to pooch kick.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] In the fourth quarter, the Bears scored on a controversial touchdown: Carl Brumbaugh handed the ball off to Nagurski, who pulled up and threw to Red Grange in the end zone for the score.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Rules at the time mandated that a forward pass had to be thrown from at least five yards behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The Spartans argued Nagurski did not drop back five yards before passing to Grange, but the touchdown stood.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The Bears later scored a safety after the Spartans fumbled the ball out of their end zone.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Because it proved so popular, the 1932 NFL Playoff Game started a new era for the National Football League and for American football in general.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Through 1932, the league had used the same rules as college football.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] Beginning with the 1933 season, the NFL introduced its own set of rules.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] NFL Commissioner Joseph Carr described the rule changes as providing better scoring opportunities, which he believed "would improve the game for both players and spectators." Carr had attended the Playoff Game, and kept a ticket stub from the game in his personal scrapbook.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] In 1933, the NFL expanded to ten teams and divided into two divisions.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] The division winners met in a scheduled championship game to determine the NFL champion.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] This game was the first time in which the NFL used an 80-yard field: the next occasion was 87 years later, when in 2019, the Raiders and Packers met at IG Field in Winnipeg for a preseason game.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] IG Field, home to the Winnipeg Blue Bombers of the Canadian Football League, normally has goal posts 110 yards apart.
[src:arena-football/1932-nfl-playoff-game] After the posts were moved for the NFL preseason game, the resulting divots in the field caused a safety hazard: to allow the game to go on, the game was played on a hastily shortened 80-yard field, with kickoffs eliminated and each team starting play at its own 15-yard line.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A 2024 reboot of the Arena Football League used the original league's rulebook with minor variations.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Through the late 1990s, the Arena Football League was the only league playing any variant of the sport designed for indoor play.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A clarification limiting the scope of its patent allowed for competing **indoor football** leagues (sometimes known as **arena leagues**) to use the same size field and most other aspects of the game.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] As a result, some non-AFL arena leagues that formed after the patent expired like the National Arena League have used rebound nets, although they no longer do.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Other leagues such as the Indoor Football League and American Indoor Football opt to not use them.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The newest league, Arena Football One, used the rebound nets as they began play in 2025.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The first demonstration of football on a small field was actually played outdoors at the original open-air Madison Square Garden.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Using nine-man sides, Pennsylvania defeated Rutgers 10–0 at the annual meeting of the Amateur Athletic Union on January 16, 1889.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Two months later, on March 7, 1889, the first documented indoor football game was an exhibition between Pennsylvania and Riverton Club at the Philadelphia Academy of Music.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Field dimensions for the 0–0 tie were no more than 200 feet long by 50 feet wide, and the exhibition was played at night under gas lamps.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Other early indoor games included two exhibitions at Madison Square Garden II in December 1890.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Springfield YMCA Training School and a Yale Senior Class team played on December 12, 1890.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] James Naismith scored a touchdown for Springfield, though Yale won the exhibition 16–10.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] (Naismith's dissatisfaction with how football transferred to the indoor surface inspired him to develop the game of basketball a year later.) The following day a second exhibition game was played, with Pennsylvania defeating Rutgers 20–12.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The field at Madison Square Garden measured 260 feet (79 m) long and 100 feet (30 m) wide.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In an exhibition at Tattersall's Pavilion in Chicago on December 16, 1893, Chicago defeated Northwestern 20–14 on a field smaller than regulation.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The first documented indoor regulation football games were those played at the Chicago Coliseum in the late 1890s.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The first such game matched Michigan against Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1896.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The match was "the first collegiate game of football played under a roof." Adding to the novelty, as daylight turned to darkness, the field inside the Coliseum was lit with electric lighting.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] With seven acres of floor space, the sprawling Coliseum is believed to have not needed any compromises to accommodate an American football field.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Although both critically and commercially successful, the Coliseum was destroyed in a fire less than two years after its opening.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] It hosted only four games, and its replacement could not accommodate an American football field.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Later, at Madison Square Garden in 1902 and 1903, there were games known as the "World Series of Pro Football." The games were played on a 70-yard by 35-yard dirt field but otherwise adhered to outdoor rules.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Poor attendance led to the tournament being discontinued after two years.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Chicago Bears of the National Football League hosted an experimental game against their crosstown rivals, the Cardinals, after the 1930 NFL season, at the indoor Chicago Stadium.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Two years later, poor weather conditions led to the Bears hosting the 1932 NFL Playoff Game against the Portsmouth Spartans (now the Detroit Lions) at the stadium.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A dirt and tanbark field measuring 80 yards long (60 yards plus two ten-yard end zones) and 45 yards wide was constructed on the arena's floor.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Chicago Stadium games were notable for introducing several rule changes, including the introduction of hash marks to keep play away from spectators who were seated next to the field (much like modern indoor football), while goal posts were moved to the goal line.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] To compensate for the smaller field, teams were "penalized" 20 yards upon crossing midfield.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In 1930, the Atlantic City Convention Center constructed a nearly full-size indoor football field, and used it for one to three games a year during the 1930s; the stadium stopped hosting games in 1940 and did not resume hosting football games until 1961.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In the 1960s, the Boardwalk Bowl, a post-season game involving small college teams, was contested at the convention center.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Bowl was an attempt to make Atlantic City more of a year-round resort in the pre-gambling era as opposed to a single-season one (the Miss America Pageant, also held at the center, likewise began as an attempt to extend the season beyond Labor Day).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Atlantic Coast Football League played its inaugural championship game at the convention center in 1962, but the game only drew 2,000 fans and the game would thereafter move to the home stadium of the team with the best regular season record.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Philadelphia-based Liberty Bowl game, which had been played at Municipal Stadium from 1959 to 1963, was moved into the Convention Center in 1964 for the contest between Utah and West Virginia.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The game drew just over 6,000 fans, though, and the Liberty Bowl moved to Memphis the next year, where it has remained.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Unlike modern indoor football, the size of the playing surface and hence the rules were essentially the same as in the standard outdoor game, with rules updated to deal with contingencies for what could happen indoors, such as a punt striking the ceiling.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The end zones were slightly shorter—eight yards instead of the standard ten (coincidentally, the eight-yard endzone length is the standard in modern indoor football).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] He devised his game while watching indoor soccer, another game derived from a sport played outdoors.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] He worked on the game in the early 1980s, but put any plans for full development of it on hold while the United States Football League, an attempt to play traditional American football in a non-traditional (spring-summer) season, was in operation in 1983–1985.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] When the USFL ceased operations, Foster saw his opportunity.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] He staged a "test" game in Rockford, Illinois in 1986 and put together a four-team league for a "demonstration season" in the spring of 1987, with games televised on ESPN.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Foster had to adopt a field that would fit within the smaller playing surfaces found in most arenas and thus created a field that was identical in size to a standard North American ice hockey rink, 200 by 85 feet (61 m × 26 m).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This resulted in the field being 50 yards long (half of the length of a standard American football field) with eight-yard end zones (which may, if necessary, be curved in the end zones as hockey rinks are), and the field being slightly over half as wide as a standard football field.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Foster adopted short-pile artificial turfs (which were then standard) such as AstroTurf for the field because of its ability to be easily rolled up when the arena is being used for other sports.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Foster adopted a modified version of eight-man football.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] He also mandated a one-platoon system that required at least six players to play on both offensive and defensive downs.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This had the added desirable effect of limiting team payrolls.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] To further an offensive passing advantage over the defense, Foster also imposed strict restrictions on the defensive formation, mandating that all defenses were required to play a 3-2-Monster formation with three defensive linemen, two linebackers, two cornerbacks, and one safety.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Linebackers were not permitted to blitz and were required to stay in boxes behind the line of scrimmage, while defensive linemen were hindered by restrictions that prevented them from using certain techniques to penetrate the offensive line.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Quarterbacks and placekickers were exempt from the one-platoon system, allowing two key scoring positions to be more specialized.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The AFL also adopted the USFL's concept of playing in the late spring and summer, since this is when most hockey and basketball arenas have the fewest schedule conflicts (only competing with touring stadium rock concerts).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The spring schedule has since been adopted by virtually all other professional indoor leagues as of 2010.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Within a year of the AFL kicking off, its first challenger, the World Indoor Football League formed.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The WIFL planned to play a schedule with six teams beginning in summer of 1988 with its own set of indoor-inspired rules, including an unusual system that would have eight men on offense and seven men on defense.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Despite having backing from former NFL players, veteran coaches, and singer John Mellencamp, the league canceled its 1988 season, folded half of its franchises (including Mellencamp's), and made an unsuccessful bid for the remaining three teams to join the AFL; the WIFL never played a single game.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In 1990, Foster patented the rules of arena football, meaning that only persons authorized by him could use his rules and his name for the sport.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] While the AFL asserted throughout the 1990s that the patent covered virtually every aspect of the game (from the 50-yard field to the eight-man format), a 1998 lawsuit (*Arena Football League v.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Professional Indoor Football League*) established that the patent specifically covered the rebound net feature, meaning that competitors could not use this aspect of the rules.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] However, under provisions of U.S. patent law, Foster's patent expired on March 27, 2007, enabling competitors to use rebound nets (at least as originally envisioned, without other innovations that he may have patented).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The AFL signed a major network television broadcasting contract with NBC, and eventually launched an official minor league, af2, beginning in 2000.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] At times over forty teams participated in this league, almost uniformly in cities which also had minor league ice hockey teams and hence suitable arenas.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Shortly before the end of 2008, the Arena Football League announced that it would not be playing a 2009 spring season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] During the previous few years, the league administrators and team owners had allowed player salaries and other costs to rise to the point where the league and many of the teams were losing a substantial amount of money.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Late in the summer of 2009, with the team owners unable to agree on a plan for making the league viable again the AFL announced that it was folding, eventually putting its assets up in a Chapter 7 bankruptcy liquidation.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The developmental af2, however, played its 2009 season as scheduled.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Most of the teams made a sustainable profit and the team owners were eager to see the league continue for another year.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] However, with the AFL owning 50.1% of the af2, it would fold if the AFL folded.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] At the end of the 2009 season, a gathering of af2 and remaining AFL team owners set out to form their own organization, originally known as Arena Football 1 (AF1).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] AF1 went on to purchase all assets of the original AFL and af2, except for a few team names and logos owned by outside parties, in a December 2009 bankruptcy auction.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Shortly after the purchase, AF1 adopted the Arena Football League name, and the AFL relaunched in 2010.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The "iron man" rule, requiring at least six of the eight players to play on both offense and defense, was dropped, but most other past AFL rules remained unchanged.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The relaunched league saw franchises return and renewed interest, but by the end of the 2017 season, almost all of the league's teams had either folded or moved to other leagues, with only the Philadelphia Soul having existed prior to 2016.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Five expansion teams, all in the Mid-Atlantic United States, were established over the next two years, before the league announced after the 2019 season that it was dissolving in a second Chapter 7 bankruptcy.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] However, on February 1, 2023, a new ownership group that had acquired the league's trademarks and social media accounts announced another revival of the league, which began play in 2024.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] On May 12, 2024, kicker Melissa Strother made an extra point while playing for the Washington Wolfpack, making her the first female player to score a point in the league.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Other indoor football leagues have been formed, without the use of the rebound nets at the ends of the field.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Like the AFL, their playing seasons are entirely or primarily outside the traditional fall/early winter season of the outdoor sport so as not to be competing with it directly for fan support.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Since the first such league, the Professional Indoor Football League, began play in the 1998, there has often been a pattern of instability.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Each off-season has seen teams jumping from league to league.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In addition, leagues have annually merged, changed names, and separated.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The organization that is most recently known as American Indoor Football (AIF) went through three names and two ownership changes in its first three seasons.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Several other indoor leagues have been announced without ever actually commencing play, or operating only briefly with a handful of teams.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Some were claimed attempts to form a second "major" league of indoor football while others were strictly efforts to form a new "minor" league.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A few leagues have achieved a certain level of stability, however.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The National Indoor Football League (NIFL) began in 2001 and was the most successful league in the early 2000s.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Indoor Football League (IFL) began in the autumn of 2008 when two already-established leagues (the Intense Football League and United Indoor Football) chose to merge into a single organization.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The IFL's expansion model has been based less on establishing new teams and more on acquiring existing teams from other leagues.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Other, regional leagues include Champions Indoor Football (CIF), the American Arena League (AAL) and National Arena League (NAL).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Both CIF and the AAL were formed by mergers of existing leagues.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The CIF was formed from a merger of the Champions Professional Indoor Football League and the Lone Star Football League in 2015.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The AAL was formed in late 2017 as the combination of three leagues that each played one season: the Can-Am Indoor Football League, Arena Pro Football, and Supreme Indoor Football.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Champions Indoor Football merged with the new Arena Football League prior to 2024.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Fan Controlled Football launched in 2021 following an interactive format inspired by video games, with "power-ups" and fans voting on plays.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] FCF suspended operations following the 2022 season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The best-known indoor women's football league was the Lingerie Football League, later rebranded the Legends Football League.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Known for its scantily-clad players and its signature event, the Lingerie Bowl (later the Legends Cup), the LFL played a variant of indoor rules with most of its games in indoor stadiums, although a few teams experimented with playing in outdoor stadiums.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The league's brief foray into Australia was played in outdoor stadiums; these teams nevertheless played under indoor football rules.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The LFL folded in 2019 and its assets were sold to Mike Ditka, whose X League has, to date, played one season in 2022.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] All other women's leagues play on outdoor fields with outdoor rules; there have been several other attempts to form indoor women's football leagues, but none have made it to play.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] As its name implies, arena football is played exclusively indoors, in arenas usually designed for either basketball or ice hockey teams.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The scrimmage area is 50 yards (46 m) long (unlike the field in NFL which is 100 yards (91 m) long), and each end zone is approximately 8 yards deep, two yards less than the standard 10 yards.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Depending on the venue in which a game is being played, the end zones may be rectangular (like a basketball court) or, where necessary because of the building design, rounded (like a hockey rink; this is much like some Canadian football fields where the end zones can be cut off by a track).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Each sideline has a heavily padded barrier, with the padding placed over the hockey dasher boards.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The goalpost uprights are 9 feet (2.7 m) wide, and the crossbar is 15 feet (4.6 m) above the playing surface, 50% narrower and higher than outdoor goalposts.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In the original form of arena football, taut rebound nets on either side of the posts bounce any missed field goals back into the field of play.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The ball is "live" when rebounding off these nets or their support apparatus.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The entire goalframe and goalside rebound net system is suspended on cables from the rafters.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The bottom of the two goalside rebound nets are 8 feet (2.4 m) off the playing surface.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Each netframe is 32 feet (9.8 m) high by 30 feet (9.1 m) wide.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A player is not counted as out of bounds on the sidelines unless he is pushed into or falls over the sideline barrier.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This rule was put in place before the 2006 season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Before that time, a sideline with only a small amount of space (typically 6" to 12") existed between the sideline stripe and the barrier which would provide the space for a ball carrier to step out of bounds before hitting the sideline barrier.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Each team fields 8 players at a time from a 21-man active roster.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Before 2007, players played both offense and defense except for the Quarterback, Kicker, and Offensive Specialist (Wide Receiver/Running Back combination) and two Defensive Specialists (Defensive Backs).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] If a player enters and leaves, from the moment he leaves the player is considered "dead" and cannot return to play until the designated time is served.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Exception: a "dead" player may participate on kickoffs, or as long snapper or holder.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In 2006, the AFL changed its substitution rules such that free substitutions were allowed on all kickoffs.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The most significant change was the introduction of free substitution, the so-called "Elway Rule".
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Previously, AFL coaches were limited to one substitution per position per quarter.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] From 2007 to 2019 and come 2024, coaches can substitute players at will.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The rationale was that free substitution would improve the overall quality of football in the league by giving coaches the freedom to put their best players on the field for every play of the game, and that teams would be able to select from a wider player talent pool when building their rosters.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The iteration of the league that began play in 2024 restored the "ironman" rules at the beginning of the season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Four offensive players must be on the line of scrimmage at the snap; one of the linemen must declare himself the tight end.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] One offensive player may be moving forward at the time of the snap as long as he has not yet crossed the line of scrimmage.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Three defensive players must be in a three- or four-point stance at the start of the snap.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Two defenders serve as linebackers, called the Mac and the Jack.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Mac may blitz from the side of the line opposite the offensive Tight End.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Jack's role has changed after new rules set in place by the league in 2008.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The Jack cannot blitz, but under new, more defense-friendly rules, the Jack Linebacker may roam sideline to sideline within five yards of the line of scrimmage and drop into coverage once the Quarterback pump fakes.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The ball is kicked off from the goal line, to start the halves and odd overtimes, or after any score.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The team with the ball is given four downs to gain ten yards or score.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Punting is illegal because of the size of the playing field, however, a field goal that either misses wide (therefore bouncing off the nets surrounding the goalposts) or falls short, may be returned.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Thus an impossibly long field goal is tantamount to a punt in other football variants.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A receiver jumping to catch a pass needs to get only one foot down in bounds for the catch to be ruled a completed catch, just as in college football.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Practically, this means that one foot must touch the ground before the receiver is pushed into the boards by an opposing player.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Passes that bounce off the rebound nets remain "live." Balls that bounce off the padded walls that surround the field are "live"; the end zone walls were not live until the 2006 season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Come 2025 gunners must line up on their own 15-yard line on kickoffs, with one receiving player fielding from the end zone.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The scoring is the same as in the NFL with the addition of a drop kick field goal worth four points during normal play or two points as a post-touchdown conversion.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Blocked extra points and turnovers on two-point conversion attempts may be returned by the defensive team for two points.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Arena Football One intends to continue the added point for a drop kick, as well as bringing in the deuce from previous fifty-yard game variants.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The league also instituted the "deuce": if a kickoff goes through the uprights, the kicking team receives two points.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This rule had previously been in effect in the IFL and the NAL.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The league also instituted the rouge / single, as used in the CFL, whereby, on a kickoff, the kicking team receives one point if the receiving team fails to bring the ball out of its own end zone.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] After scoring a touchdown, the scoring team has the option of attempting a four-point conversion (akin to the three-point conversion seen in the UFL and its predecessors) from the opponent's ten-yard line, alongside the existing extra point and two-point conversion options.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The rule was carried over as part of a pre-launch merger with Champions Indoor Football.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Teams may go for two points from the 2.5-yard line, and before it was rescinded, three from the 5, or four from the 10, after any touchdown, if they want to.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Arena Football One rescinded the three-point and four-point conversions along with the single from its rulebook in 2025, while keeping the deuce.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The single was restored to the rulebook in 2026.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Coaches are given two challenges per game, as in the NFL; to challenge, they must throw their red flag before the next play.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] If the play stands as called after review, the challenging team loses a timeout.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] If a team wins both challenges used, a third is granted.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Video review is automatic in the final half-minute of regulation, all overtime periods, and all scoring plays and turnovers.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A game has four 15-minute quarters with a 15-minute halftime (ArenaBowl has a 30-minute interval).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Teams are allowed three timeouts per half, and two per overtime period if regulation ends tied.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Teams must use a timeout if there's an injury inside a half-minute left in regulation or overtime; exception applies to when team has no timeouts, and this occurs, they're granted an extra timeout.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The clock also stops for any change in possession, until the ball is marked ready for play; for example, aside from the final half-minute of regulation or overtime, time continues to run down after a touchdown, but stops after an extra point or two-point conversion attempt.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] If a quarter ends as a touchdown is scored, an untimed conversion attempt takes place.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The play clock is 30 seconds, starting at the end of the previous play.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In all arenas, the final minute of the period is measured in tenths of a second.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Prior to the 2018 season, during the final minute of the fourth quarter, the clock stopped if the offensive team had the lead and did not advance the ball past the line of scrimmage.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This prevented the "victory formation" (the offensive team merely kneeling down), or running other plays that are designed solely to exhaust the remaining time rather than to advance the ball downfield.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This rule was eliminated in the interest of player safety.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In the first overtime, each team gets one possession to score.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Whoever is ahead after one possession wins.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] If the teams are tied after each has had a possession, true sudden death rules apply thereafter.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Each overtime period is 15 minutes, and continues from the ending of the previous overtime period until the tie is broken.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] All overtimes thereafter are true sudden death; no games can be tied.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] This includes both games of all semifinal series.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Before the 2007 season, there was one 15-minute overtime period, and if it expired with the teams still tied, the game was recorded as a tie.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] A July 25, 2015 game between the Las Vegas Outlaws and New Orleans VooDoo that was never played was also recorded as a scoreless tie.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Before 2007, the play clock was 25 seconds, and it began on the signal from the referee.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] All current indoor football teams play at a minor league or semi-professional level.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The average player's salary in the Arena Football League was US$1,800 per game in 2008; this is about one-quarter of the Canadian Football League (adjusted for inflation).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] As of 2019, the IFL pays $200–$300 per game, with a $25 bonus for each win.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The 2024 revival of the AFL originally promised $1,000 per game, but this was soon rolled back to $250 per game (the salary of Champions Indoor Football in 2023) for most teams when the league reorganized.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Arena Football One pays a base salary of $400 per week with players allowed to sign a personal service contract for more money.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The NAL maximum per-player salary is $600 per game as of 2025.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Some AFL players have gone on to have successful careers in the National Football League, most notably Kurt Warner.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Warner played college football at University of Northern Iowa and then quarterbacked the AFL's Iowa Barnstormers to ArenaBowl X in 1996 and ArenaBowl XI in 1997, before earning two NFL MVP Awards, a Super Bowl MVP Award and quarterbacking the St.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Louis Rams and the Arizona Cardinals to the Super Bowl, winning Super Bowl XXXIV with the Rams.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Warner was later inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame, the only person to play a substantial portion of his professional career (as opposed to a short publicity stunt, as was the case with Joe DeLamielleure's brief tenure in the sport) playing arena football.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Another, probably the second most notable behind Warner, could be Fred Jackson.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Jackson played indoor football with the Sioux City Bandits in 2004 when they played in the NIFL (2004) and the UIF in 2005 before finally moving on to NFL Europa's Rhein Fire in 2006, then to the NFL after Rhein.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Other AFL to NFL graduates include Anthony Armstrong, Oronde Gadsden, Lincoln Coleman, Adrian McPherson, Rashied Davis, Jay Feely, David Patten, Rob Bironas, Antonio Chatman, Mike Vanderjagt, and Paul Justin.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Former Arena Football League MVP Jay Gruden (brother of Jon Gruden) went on to coach the Orlando Predators of the AFL, Florida Tuskers of the United Football League, and then the head coach for the Washington Redskins in the NFL.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Eddie Brown, voted in 2006 as the greatest player in AFL history, never played in the NFL, but his son Antonio Brown joined the Pittsburgh Steelers in 2010 and was voted to the Pro Bowl in 2011 and in every season from 2013 to 2018.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Matt Nagy was a quarterback in the AFL from 2002 to 2008 and became the head coach of the Chicago Bears in 2018.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Green Bay Packers head coach Matt LaFleur was a quarterback for the Omaha Beef and the Billings Outlaws in the National Indoor Football League (NIFL).
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Running back Fred Jackson rushed for over 1,000 yards as the starting running back for the 2009 Buffalo Bills, and his high quality play earned him a spot on *USA Today'*s "All-Joe" Team.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Jackson played the early part of his professional football career for the Sioux City Bandits (now of Champions Indoor Football) and Michael Lewis played for the Louisiana Bayou Beast in 1999 and then with the New Orleans Saints.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The National Football League removed a ban that had been in place on any of its owners owning teams in any other sort of football operation with respect to Arena football only, and several of them had bought or started Arena teams at one point.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Several NFL owners owned Arena Football League teams in their own cities prior to the league's bankruptcy.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] San Francisco 49ers owner Denise DeBartolo York and the Washington Commanders owner Daniel Snyder had future expansion rights to their respective cities.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Tom Benson's original New Orleans VooDoo and Bud Adams's Nashville Kats had already folded prior to the bankruptcy and none of the NFL owners with AFL franchises returned to the league after its reformation in 2010, and most favored abolishing the league entirely.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Dozens of former and current professional outdoor football players also have invested money into indoor football franchises.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] The IFL had a formal minor league partnership with the XFL in its 2023 season.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Several arena football video games and trading card sets have been released.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Upper Deck released AFL trading card sets in 2005 and 2006.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] Even though arena football is a relatively young sport, it has appeared in various forms of popular culture over the course of its existence.
[src:arena-football/arena-football] In 2014, AMC aired the reality television series *4th and Loud*, following the first season of the LA Kiss and its owners, including Doc McGee and Kiss bandmates Paul Stanley and Gene Simmons.
